eq a_{12}
eq a_{13}$, $a_{21}
eq a_{22}
eq a_{23}$, and so on, where $a_{ij}=	ext{character}$ at the $i^{	ext{th}}$ row and $j^{	ext{th}}$ column. The total number of ways this can be done is $6\cdot5\cdot4\cdot3\cdot2\cdot1\cdot1=720$. Since there are $2^7=128$ ways to create MI triplets for each $7$ characters, $N=720\cdot128=92160\equiv 616 \pmod{1000}$.</think> 

We then note that we can select six numbers from the set $\{1,2,3,4,5,6,7\}$ in $\dbinom{7}{6}=7$ ways, and the six numbers can be grouped in $\dbinom{6}{3}=20$ ways. Thus the number of minimally intersecting ordered triples of sets for which each set is a subset of $\{1,2,3,4,5,6,7\}$ is $N=7	imes 20=140$, and the remainder when $N$ is divided by $1000$ is $140$.
